const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why does my Viking range keep clicking even when the burner is lit?",
    a: "Continuous clicking after a burner is already lit is almost always a moisture issue. Water has gotten into the igniter switch housing — usually from cleaning, a spill, or coastal humidity — and the spark electrode keeps firing because the switch contacts are wet. Let the range air-dry for 2-4 hours with all burners off. In coastal Malibu and Newport Beach homes, this can take longer due to ambient humidity. If clicking continues after complete drying, reseat the burner cap firmly — even 1mm of misalignment on Viking 5 Series burner caps can prevent the flame sensor from reading correctly and keep the igniter active. If clicking continues across multiple burners after drying and reseating, the spark module itself needs replacement — a professional repair."
  },
  {
    q: "What does F02 mean on my Viking range?",
    a: "F02 is a temperature sensor fault — the oven's RTD probe is reading outside its expected resistance range, either shorted, open, or physically damaged. The correct diagnosis is to test the probe resistance before assuming the control board has failed. The probe is a $60-90 OEM Viking part. The control board is $400+. We see F02 misdiagnosed as a board failure regularly. The probe mounts inside the oven cavity and is straightforward to replace when it's confirmed as the fault. If the probe tests correctly and F02 persists, then the board becomes the next diagnostic step."
  },
