  <section class="brand-context">
    <div class="brand-context-inner">
      <div class="section-number">03</div>
      <div class="brand-context-content">
        <h2>The Viking Range Igniter — Why SoCal Is Different</h2>
        <p>Burner ignition failure accounts for roughly 40% of Viking range service calls we handle across all three counties. The root cause varies depending on where in Southern California you live, and understanding the pattern helps explain why certain homes see this failure earlier than others.</p>
        <p>The most common cause everywhere: moisture in the igniter housing after cleaning. Water gets into the spark electrode area, the igniter fires continuously even when the burner is off or lit, and sometimes multiple burners fail to light entirely if the moisture has reached the spark module. The fix is usually drying — 2-4 hours with all burners off, then reseating the burner caps. In most inland locations, this resolves the issue completely.</p>
        <p>In coastal homes within a mile or two of the Pacific — Malibu beachfront, Newport Peninsula, Balboa Island, Dana Point Harbor area — salt air creates an accelerated corrosion environment. The metal igniter electrode tips corrode within 3-5 years regardless of how carefully the range is cleaned. The ceramic housing develops micro-cracks that allow salt moisture to reach the metal. The symptom is gradual: first occasional slow ignition, then clicking without lighting on specific burners, then complete failure. We replace corroded electrodes with OEM Viking parts and recommend quarterly cleaning with a non-acidic food-safe degreaser, plus an annual igniter inspection for ocean-adjacent properties.</p>
        <p>In the Ventura County communities and canyon homes above West LA — Thousand Oaks, Agoura Hills, Westlake Village, Malibu Canyon — wildfire smoke ash has become a documented cause of ignition problems. Fine ash particles infiltrate kitchen ventilation during fire events and settle inside burner assemblies and igniter housings. Ash is mildly acidic and accelerates electrode corrosion. After significant fire events in the area, we now proactively recommend inspecting all burner assemblies — and we find ash contamination regularly on post-fire calls in these communities.</p>

        <h2>Protecting Your Viking Investment</h2>
        <p>A Viking Professional 5 Series range starts at around $5,000 and goes to $10,000+ for large dual-fuel configurations. A Viking built-in refrigerator runs $7,000-12,000. These are significant investments, and homeowners reasonably ask whether an older unit is worth repairing.</p>
        <p>Our honest answer: Viking ranges and refrigerators are designed for 15-20 year lifespans. The sealed refrigeration system and the gas valve infrastructure are the components that determine actual useful life — and these typically remain healthy for well beyond a decade with appropriate maintenance. The components that wear out — fan motors, igniter electrodes, temperature sensors, control boards — are all serviceable. Repairing them extends the life of a fundamentally sound appliance at a fraction of replacement cost.</p>
        <p>The exception: when we see a refrigerator with a sealed system issue (compressor, refrigerant leak, evaporator failure) on a unit that's already 12-15 years old, or a range with multiple simultaneous failures suggesting a broader electrical issue, we tell the homeowner that honestly. We never recommend a repair that doesn't make economic sense relative to the appliance's condition and replacement cost.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

